<user>105513414444568762399</user><name>v R</name><Date>1558545014952<//Date><Rating>4</Rating>< text>
Great park! Ample space, has several stair areas, not to mention rails and less steep ramps. Good for beginners because there's space to practice without getting in the way. There are also benches with tables for mom's or girlfriends who want to wait around. There's decent shade . One caveat is it's right next to the freeway, so I imagine prolonged physical activity by all the car muck can't be too good. And there was trash and graffiti, as is usual in these types of parks.<//text>

< review>
The only reason I donâ€™t want to give a 5 Star review is due to the fact that this is, by far, one of my favorite skate spots and Iâ€™d rather not see it get any busier than it can already get. Itâ€™s such a great park though, that giving anything less would fail to give the park justice.

Itâ€™s a fairly large sized park- plenty of open room to practice riding if youâ€™re new, as well as obstacles for every skill level - I often go with my girlfriend who is still learning how to even ride a board and she also says itâ€™s one of her favorite parks. Whether youâ€™re an advanced skater, or itâ€™s your very first time on a board, thereâ€™s something for everyone at this park.

Iâ€™ve personally never had any kind of trouble with regards to any riff raff or anything - in fact, I often see children and their parents show up early to skate, and have even seen someone in a wheel chair doing their thing throughout the park (very cool!) and Iâ€™ve certainly never once witnessed any â€œsexual actsâ€ like another review stated they had LOL. Further more, the graffiti throughout the park compliments the park immensely, giving it not only a unique sense of â€œcharacterâ€ but actually enhancing the park by adding some vibrant color and a touch of art that was brought to the park by none other than the skaters themselves. I think itâ€™s great that members of the community have had a safe place to express themselves in a place that they regularly visit and skate, and it was done so artistically and it only adds to the already great park. The park is also well kept, clean, and I often see the local skaters sweeping it themselves and picking up trash - the park is never dirty and is well maintained. Thereâ€™s minimal shade, which is one of the only complaints I could really have about the park. So it gets hot mid-day/afternoon.

I pass several parks on my way to this one nearly every day, and while some of those parks are good parks that I also enjoy skating, sheldon is by far one of my favorites and is a great place to skate. 5\5 for sure, absolutely worthy of checking out.<//review>

<Response>None< /Response>< text>
Dishonesty and predatory behavior runs rampant through the entire staff.

Josh (the newest sales manager) and Winn VW care more about nickel and diming their customers than conducting business in an honest manner to earn a reputation that could keep them in business and good standing with their community. It's really sad they have to resort to dishonesty and fraud to make their numbers.

Timeline of my disgusting experience:
1. Jan 2020 - We researched and found a Certified Pre Owned Jetta with under 7000 miles that fit our needs for a simple commuter car to park next to our brand new BMW.

2. The car was advertised as having a clean 'CARFAX' and the salesman reiterated over and over again that this was a barely used vehicle with a pristine record.

3. After signing all of the paperwork and about to take delivery we're informed that there's only 1 key for the car and an additional key could be purchased for $200. Obviously undoing the previous hour of financial paperwork and signed contracts was not in our interest considering we had our young daughter with us. We took delivery and got the extra key.

4. When we purchased the vehicle, though we had every intention of paying cash for this little car, we were strongly asked to finance the car for 6 months to unlock an incentive for the dealership. We begrudgingly agreed.

5. March 2020 - COVID hit. We left the area and no longer needed this car. Out of respect for the promise we made we parked the car at a friends in the area until those 6 small little payments were made to help the dealership (per our spoken agreement) get their incentive from VW (they were gaming the system...but we were just trying to help them out).

6. Car was paid off in July.  I listed the car for sale on cargurus and solicited a quote from Carvana. Carvana reported that the car was worth $1500 less than market value due to a 'multi impact' accident that took place (in the same county as the dealership). CARFAX competitor 'Autocheck' has become industry standard to protect consumers and they clearly list the accident.7. I contacted the dealership. The salesman we worked with had quit. I spoke to the sales manager, produced the autocheck report and he was very sympathetic to the fact that their dealership had committed fraud by repeatedly stating that the car had never sustained any damage. They continue to do so by relisting this vehicle on cargurus with a 'clean CARFAX' clearly knowing that car was in a major accident.

8. The sales manager offered to match carvana's offer without the accident, plus met me closer to the 'auction' value of the car as an apology for this dishonest business practice of his dealership. Though I felt entitled to a full refund for being sold a car with falsified information, we agreed I'd have my friend drop the car with the title to accept his offer.

9. That sales manager, 'Sinbad', quit the day before we brought the car in. The current sales manager Josh Nguyen now defended the nefarious actions of the dealership and told me CARFAX was industry standard and WINN VW has no obligation to rely on or reference any other service and is fully entitled to represent a clean record on the car. Proven by the fact that he fraudulently listed the vehicle with a 'CLEAN CARFAX' again on Cargurus (for $3000 more than he paid me)

10. Josh decided to undermine Sinbad's offer and told me hed pay about $500 less. "If you don't like it... come 'get your car' (knowing that this was being done remotely) he said. I compelled him to contact Sinbad, who now says he has 'no recollection of the details of our agreement' but would meet me in the middle ($250 less than his offer and more than Josh's).

11. Winn VW sent me a check for $9000 OVER their lowest offer. My multiple calls to Josh to understand what was going on were unreturned. A check arrived 3 days later for the lowest amount ($500 less than the initial offer) which was cashed.

The deal was agreed on at one number. The car and title were dropped and they tried to drop it $500. We agreed in the middle. They sent the low check anyway.<//text>

<review>Buying a new car is generally regarded as a bad experience. Whether you're seeking advice from friends, online articles or YouTube, you'll find no shortage of horror stories where people are swindled and backstabbed at every opportunity when they try to negotiate on the price of a car - the industry has earned itself a poor reputation from decades of deception and con-artistry. I got a taste of this at a San Jose Volkswagen dealership, where the sales manager arrogantly put down any attempt at negotiation and ruined the chance of a sale.

From my first time through their doors, Winn Volkswagen defied the stereotype. The staff wasn't just friendly, they were personable. There weren't any games, no backdoor deals or thinly-disguised lies; everything was straightforward, and we were able to negotiate a deal that was so much better than any of the other Bay Area dealerships could offer.
At the end of the day, I got the exact Volkswagen I wanted at a price that leaves other people envious.

Incredibly, the VW dealership nearest to me was by far the best. When the time comes to buy a new car again, Winn Volkswagen will be my first choice.<//review>< pictures>

<Review>This place is literally a scam! If you don't want to read the entire post (I get it), just take my warning and do not buy a used car from these people.

I saw this car online and it had all of the specs that I was looking for at a reasonable price point. I called the dealership and they put it aside for me until I could come take a look and ultimately purchase a couple of days later. When I arrived the drivers side mirror was TAPED on. It was clearly falling off, and when I asked if it would be repaired before I made the purchase the salesmen said no. I clearly stated that I would not be purchasing a car with a taped on mirror. He just said "it's a used car, it has flaws."

I was already there so I agreed to go for a test drive. When the taped on mirror wouldn't move when I went to adjust it, that's when he said he would be willing to have it fixed.

There were a few little imperfections in the car, and every time I asked about them I was told, "it's a used car." Right. I get it.

Finally, I decided to make the purchase, I was sick of looking for a car and I was already there. MISTAKE!

I didn't have any major hassle with the purchase process. I got a great interest rate as VW has fantastic CPO financing.

I picked the car up after a few days of waiting for that taped on mirror to be fixed.

Side note: the horn doesn't work well, and the gas cap was broken... Things you forget to check when you are purchasing a used car. Learn from my mistakes... honk the horn and pull out the gas cap. I decided to live with these imperfections. It is a used car after all :/

After a few months I still hadn't gotten my license plates. When I inquired about this I was told that they hadn't smogged the car and that I needed to get it smogged. I took it in and the car DID NOT PASS. They told me I had to bring it back to the dealership and they would take care of it. The dealership is not convenient for me to get to, so I said they could pick it up and take care of it. Then out of nowhere, they produce a passed smog form and get the car registered (still not sure what shady stuff went on to get that done).

Now, almost a year later, I go to get my car serviced and the mechanic said that they will not rotate the tires because they are destroyed. He asked me if I frequently drive on loose gravel... I do not. So, now I need new tires and the mechanic said that these tires really should have another 40k miles as they are really nice. But that's not all... the wheels are locked and I don't have a key for them. I've searched, two tire shops have searched, I don't have it. I called the dealer asking them to reimburse me to have the locks removed at a dealer near me (they don't make the lug keys for this car anymore), it's going to be $70. Not a lot, but I'm about to drop $600 on new tires that I shouldn't need, so every bit counts. They said they'll remove the locks at the dealership, but won't reimburse me to get it done at a dealership near me.<//Review>< Pictures>

<rating>5< /rating><review>We were greeted on the phone by a courteous Erick, and when we came in to the dealership, he made sure someone took us out for a test drive even though he had a prior appointment. Louis from sales came out and cleared everything up, and then we went into his office to work out the terms.

We were able to work out a very good deal, which made us really happy about this major investment we got into. < name>
Jason Burleigh< /name>
<Rate>1< /Rate><Resp>None< /Resp><date>1613166424176<//date><Pictures>None< /Pictures><review>I recently bought work van to start a business for myself. The van did not pass smog and needed some smog repairs. After failing the smog test, I immediately drove it to Midas, because I am still rather new to the West Side, and I haven't used any other mechanics in this area. I assumed that Midas was qualified to do the repairs...

I explained my situation to David at the front desk, and he reassured me multiple times that everything would be taken care of. I was very clear that I needed the vehicle to pass smog, and that smog repairs were my only reason for coming to the shop.

The following day I received a call from David informing me that the van had a couple check engine lights, one for a MAF sensor and another for misfires. He explained that the vehicle had not received new spark plugs in a long time and was probably misfiring due to needing a tune up. He convinced me to spend a few hundred bucks on a tune up and said I would be good to go. They also replaced a MAF and something else... After it was all said and done the repairs were just under $700.

I take the vehicle to get the smog test done and it fails again. I immediately call Midas and they assure me that I have not driven the van enough to reset the monitors, and to drive the van 60 miles, then I will be good to go. So I do this, then take it back to Midas and have them check it again, and it is still showing check engine lights. They tell me that I still have not driven the van enough, after I drove it close it 100 miles. So I drove it another 75-100 miles and brought it back again. The check it again and the check engine light still wont go away.

David recommends me to LARSENS AUTOMOTIVE (best thing that came out of this whole experience, highly recommend LARSEN AUTOMOTIVE)

I go to Larsen's and wow, what a breath of fresh air. I cannot even begin to explain the difference in quality of mechanics, service, and expertise. The guys at Larsen's really know what they are talking about. The first thing that they told me at Larsen's is that only CALIFORNIA CERTIFIED SMOG REPAIR STATIONS should be doing the work. Because if it does not pass, which it did not, the repairs must have been done at a certified shop in order to have the Smog waivered.....

WOW. Thanks a lot Midas. Now the $700 I spent is worthless to the DMV because you are NOT CERTIFIED to do smog repairs. I must spend another $650 at a CERTIFIED smog repair station...Larsen's informs me that because I already spent the money, my best option would be to see if Midas can complete the repairs and get the vehicle to pass smog.

Larsen's preforms their own diagnostic test and explains that the problems causing the vehicle to fail the smog test were NEVER properly diagnosed or addressed, and that all they did was do a tune up and call it a day. Larsen's had a very clear understanding of the problems and what steps needed to be taken to resolve them.

I went back to Midas with this information and they agreed to look at the vehicle further. After several days they called me to explain that they had given up. They were unable to solve the issues and were not going to continue working on the vehicle.

They then returned the van to me with less than 1 quart of oil in the engine. When I asked about this the mechanic explain that he checked the oil, so it must have all leaked out. So I asked him if he had a puddle of oil anywhere with 4 quarts of oil on the ground, but he said no. So I am not sure where he thinks 4 quarts of oil disappeared to between the time he claims to have checked it and the time they gave it back to me. (Grade A mechanic)

So here I am now stuck with a van that will not pass smog. It still needs over $1k in repairs, and the DMV will not waiver the test because the repairs were not preformed at a certified repair station.

Thanks a lot Midas. I will be pursuing this is court for misrepresentation.<//review>< gmap_id>

Fork damper rebuilt
Rear axle/free hub replaced
Drivetrain repaired
Dropper seatpost (which I didnâ€™t even buy from them and was out of warranty) replaced.
Broken rear chainstay replaced.

I am currently buying an ebike from them, and they have been wonderful to work with, as I get a 2019 model where there are limited amounts of in the country, and getting it quickly and effectively.

< review>
I had not purchased a new mountain bike in 22 years, and hadn't been on one at all in almost 10. I visited Wheel World because I was interested in a Giant mountain bike and this was the closest dealership to me. What good fortune! Cailen greeted me as I walked in the door. I told him about my long absence from mountain biking, and asked him if the bike I was considering was a good choice. He guided me through the differences and features of bikes in my price range (and out) and eventually pointed me in the direction of a closeout 2017 model that had $300 more features than the bike I was considering for only $100 more. The bike is a great fit for me and I am very happy with it. Not only that, the team at Wheel World is excellent with service after the sale. I had a flat after my second ride, and went in thinking I'd have to leave the wheel there. Even though they were slammed,  they had the tire changed and back in my hands in 5 minutes! This is an exemplary bike shop. As long as I live in this area I won't shop anywhere else.</review>

I travelled with my bike. Just got in town, and chain broken when taken out of bike box. On recommendation of my host I'm staying with, I brought it in to Wheel World. I had known this before travel, but because of time constraints, didn't get it dealt with. <Date>1496522716813<//Date>< review>
Generally speaking, its not a bad location... I dont like that I have overheard the employees talking about inappropriate topics while the lobby was largely empty (save me and one or two others, Ive never heard t), though I suppose I can understand that this location has that type of camaraderie (though not all of them do it, theres one heavy set dark skinned guy with glasses that is really cool, calm, and respectful and he always gets my drink right), and it can get loud and obnoxious when the kids come though after there school gets out (kids will be kids though, I suppose).

However, when someone loses sense of professionalism when dealing with a customer (even in general but its worse when doing so directly) then that is the time people need to step back and realize that they need to re evaluate there conduct.

Yes, yes, I am responding to a personal slight. All I said above was true though and I took the time to calm down and think about things before I decided to write this review.

In there defense, they where mostly calm and they listened when I approached them about what I saw as a slight against me. They tried to apologize but ultimately I did not feel it was sincere because they where asking me what I heard and after I stepped away to calm down and came back to ask that one employee (cool guy) to take my order instead the first one decides to come back and accuse me of conducting violence upon the stores property. I am offended, not angry. I think initially described myself as perturbed to them though so I suppose I can understand that they may have felt I was upset enough to try to take out my anger on something.

There is a great deal I wanted to say, however I figured I felt more indignant then the situation warranted (part of the reason I stepped away before coming back to order my drink) and so the only thing I was holding back that I felt compelled to express was words... not actions.< /review>

<userid>107693513493878426669< /userid><username>Morison Woo<//username>< date>
1450403384454</date>
<Rating>4<//Rating><review>This place has really good drinks and food! I'm so glad I got to try this place out. Even though it is a bit out of the way and fairly hidden, I would recommend trying this place at least once.

I would not say this place is necessarily good for huge groups. If you like loud, rowdy places like Gaam in Ktown, then this won't be it. This is better for smaller groups that just want a chill place.

Drinks: Blue Lemon Soju. Must get! This is really good. Pretty much like lemonade.

Food: Egg Bomb Fries!! This is exactly like it sounds. Super bomb!! Loved the sunny side up egg on top too.
Spoon Pizza: This is a little different than actual pizza.. It's not exactly like a pizza because it has potato on the bottom. So you can eat this dish with a spoon. It's a little different, but still good.

Vibe: They try to keep a trendy feel by playing some Edm once in a while. But it's definitely not big enough to fit a lot of people inside.</review><pics>None< /pics>< response>
None</response>

<Review>Cool, new bar on the edge of Ktown! Their decor is really cool and spacious. Their food is pretty good and their drinks are really cool too. They have a wide array of beer and wine along with soju and surprisingly champagne! Prices are decent and they also have cool cocktails. The only thing is that it is predominantly Koreans. It was kind of difficult to communicate with the waiters and felt like they werent as friendly to us because we werent fluent in Korean. The waiters went around to each table, striking conversation and taking shots with the customers. Other than the language barrier, everything else was good.

-Blue lemon soju cocktail was really good. Has a hint of coconut.
-bomb fries are really good
-spoon pizza has no bread and is like just cheese and tomato sauce with veggies like sweet potato, onions, green pepper, and tomatoes inside.</Review>< Pics>
